# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gyroscope-mems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In physics, the **Coriolis force** is a pseudo-force that acts on objects in motion within a frame of reference that rotates with respect to an inertial frame.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In a reference frame with clockwise rotation, the force acts to the left of the motion of the object.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In one with anticlockwise (or counterclockwise) rotation, the force acts to the right.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Deflection of an object due to the Coriolis force is called the **Coriolis effect**.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Though recognized previously by others, the mathematical expression for the Coriolis force appeared in an 1835 paper by French scientist Gaspard-Gustave de Coriolis, in connection with the theory of water wheels.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Early in the 20th century, the term *Coriolis force* began to be used in connection with meteorology.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] On Earth, the Coriolis force will affect the movement of air and water over long distance.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Because of Earth's rotation, the moving object does not travel in a straight line relative to the Earth's surface but follows a curved path.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] This deflection (clockwise in the Northern Hemisphere and counterclockwise in the Southern Hemisphere) significantly influences large-scale circulation of winds and ocean currents.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Newton's laws of motion describe the motion of an object in an inertial (non-accelerating) frame of reference.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] When Newton's laws are transformed to a rotating frame of reference, the Coriolis and centrifugal accelerations appear.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] When applied to objects with masses, the respective forces are proportional to their masses.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The magnitude of the Coriolis force is proportional to the rotation rate, and the magnitude of the centrifugal force is proportional to the square of the rotation rate.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The centrifugal force acts outwards in the radial direction and is proportional to the distance of the body from the axis of the rotating frame.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] These additional forces are termed inertial forces, fictitious forces, or *pseudo forces*.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] By introducing these fictitious forces to a rotating frame of reference, Newton's laws of motion can be applied to the rotating system as though it were an inertial system; these forces are correction factors that are not required in a non-rotating system.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In popular (non-technical) usage of the term "Coriolis effect", the rotating reference frame implied is almost always the Earth.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Because the Earth rotates, Earth-bound observers need to account for the Coriolis force to correctly analyze the motion of objects.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Such motions are constrained by the surface of the Earth, so only the horizontal component of the Coriolis force is generally important.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] This force causes moving objects on the surface of the Earth to be deflected to the right (with respect to the direction of travel) in the Northern Hemisphere and to the left in the Southern Hemisphere.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The horizontal deflection effect is greater near the poles, since the effective rotation rate about a local vertical axis is largest there, and decreases to zero at the equator.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Rather than flowing directly from areas of high pressure to low pressure, as they would in a non-rotating system, winds and currents tend to flow to the right of this direction north of the equator ("clockwise") and to the left of this direction south of it ("anticlockwise").
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] This effect is responsible for the rotation and thus formation of cyclones .
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Italian scientist Giovanni Battista Riccioli and his assistant Francesco Maria Grimaldi described the effect in connection with artillery in the 1651 *Almagestum Novum*, writing that rotation of the Earth should cause a cannonball fired to the north to deflect to the east.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In 1674, Claude François Milliet Dechales described in his *Cursus seu Mundus Mathematicus* how the rotation of the Earth should cause a deflection in the trajectories of both falling bodies and projectiles aimed toward one of the planet's poles.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Riccioli, Grimaldi, and Dechales all described the effect as part of an argument against the heliocentric system of Copernicus.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In other words, they argued that the Earth's rotation should create the effect, and so failure to detect the effect was evidence for an immobile Earth.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Their arguments were correct, but the effect of Coriolis force is so small that it was not measured until the 19th century.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The Coriolis acceleration equation was derived by Euler in 1749, and the effect was described in the tidal equations of Pierre-Simon Laplace in 1778.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Gaspard-Gustave de Coriolis published a paper in 1835 on the energy yield of machines with rotating parts, such as waterwheels.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] That paper considered the supplementary forces that are detected in a rotating frame of reference.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Coriolis divided these supplementary forces into two categories.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The second category contained a force that arises from the cross product of the angular velocity of a coordinate system and the projection of a particle's velocity into a plane perpendicular to the system's axis of rotation.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Coriolis referred to this force as the "compound centrifugal force" due to its analogies with the centrifugal force already considered in category one.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The effect was known in the early 20th century as the "acceleration of Coriolis", and by 1920 as "Coriolis force".
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In 1856, William Ferrel proposed the existence of a circulation cell in the mid-latitudes with air being deflected by the Coriolis force to create the prevailing westerly winds.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The understanding of the kinematics of how exactly the rotation of the Earth affects airflow was partial at first.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Late in the 19th century, the full extent of the large scale interaction of pressure-gradient force and deflecting force that in the end causes air masses to move along isobars was understood.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The fictitious forces as they are perceived in the rotating frame act as additional forces that contribute to the apparent acceleration just like the real external forces.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] As seen in these formulas the Euler and centrifugal forces depend on the position vector $\mathbf {r} '$ of the object, while the Coriolis force depends on the object's velocity $\mathbf {v} '$ as measured in the rotating reference frame.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] As expected, for a non-rotating inertial frame of reference $({\boldsymbol {\omega }}=0)$ the Coriolis force and all other fictitious forces disappear.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] As the Coriolis force is proportional to a cross product of two vectors, it is perpendicular to both vectors, in this case the object's velocity and the frame's rotation vector.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] For an intuitive explanation of the origin of the Coriolis force, consider an object moving northward on the ground in the Northern Hemisphere.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Viewed from outer space, the object does not appear to go due north, but has an eastward motion (it rotates around toward the right along with the surface of the Earth).
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The further north it travels, the smaller the "radius of its parallel (latitude)" (the minimum distance from the surface point to the axis of rotation, which is in a plane orthogonal to the axis), and so the slower the eastward motion of its surface.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] As the object moves north it has a tendency to maintain the eastward speed it started with (rather than slowing down to match the reduced eastward speed of local objects on the Earth's surface), so it veers east (i.e. to the right of its initial motion).
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Though not obvious from this example, which considers northward motion, the horizontal deflection occurs equally for objects moving eastward or westward (or in any other direction).
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] However, the theory that the effect determines the rotation of draining water in a household bathtub, sink or toilet has been repeatedly disproven by modern-day scientists; the force is negligibly small compared to the many other influences on the rotation.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The time, space, and velocity scales are important in determining the importance of the Coriolis force.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] For example, in tornadoes, the Rossby number is large, so the Coriolis force is negligible; the balance is between pressure and centrifugal forces.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In low-pressure systems the Rossby number is low, as the centrifugal force is negligible; the balance is between Coriolis and pressure forces.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In oceanic systems the Rossby number is often around 1, with all three forces comparable.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] An atmospheric system moving at *U* = 10 m/s (22 mph) occupying a spatial distance of *L* = 1,000 km (621 mi), has a Rossby number of approximately 0.1.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] An unguided missile can travel far enough and be in the air long enough to experience the effect of Coriolis force.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Long-range shells in the Northern Hemisphere can land to the right of where they were aimed until the effect was noted (those fired in the Southern Hemisphere landed to the left.) It was this effect that first drew the attention of Coriolis himself.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The figures illustrate a ball tossed from 12:00 o'clock toward the center of a counter-clockwise rotating carousel.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In the first figure, the ball is seen by a stationary observer above the carousel, and the ball travels in a straight line slightly to the right of the center, because it had an initial tangential velocity given by the rotation (blue arrow) and a radial velocity given by the thrower (green arrow).
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The resulting combined velocity is shown as a solid red line, and the trajectory is shown as a dotted red line.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In the second figure, the ball is seen by an observer rotating with the carousel, so the ball-thrower appears to stay at 12:00 o'clock, and the ball trajectory has a slight curve.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The figure describes a more complex situation where the tossed ball on a turntable bounces off the edge of the carousel and then returns to the tosser, who catches the ball.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The effect of Coriolis force on its trajectory is shown again as seen by two observers: an observer (referred to as the "camera") that rotates with the carousel, and an inertial observer.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The figure shows a bird's-eye view based upon the same ball speed on forward and return paths.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Within each circle, plotted dots show the same time points.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In the left panel, from the camera's viewpoint at the center of rotation, the tosser (smiley face) and the rail both are at fixed locations, and the ball makes a very considerable arc on its travel toward the rail, and takes a more direct route on the way back.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] From the ball tosser's viewpoint, the ball seems to return more quickly than it went (because the tosser is rotating toward the ball on the return flight).
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The ball appears to bear to the left from direction of travel on both inward and return trajectories.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The curved path demands this observer to recognize a leftward net force on the ball.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] When a path curves away from radial, however, centrifugal force contributes significantly to deflection.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The ball's path through the air is straight when viewed by observers standing on the ground (right panel).
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In the right panel (stationary observer), the ball tosser (smiley face) is at 12 o'clock and the rail the ball bounces from is at position 1.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] From the inertial viewer's standpoint, positions 1, 2, and 3 are occupied in sequence.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] At position 2, the ball strikes the rail, and at position 3, the ball returns to the tosser.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Straight-line paths are followed because the ball is in free flight, so this observer requires that no net force is applied.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In the Northern Hemisphere, where the latitude is positive, this acceleration, as viewed from above, is to the right of the direction of motion.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Conversely, it is to the left in the southern hemisphere.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Consider a location with latitude *φ* on a sphere that is rotating around the north–south axis.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] A local coordinate system is set up with the *x* axis horizontally due east, the *y* axis horizontally due north and the *z* axis vertically upwards.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] For such cases, only the horizontal (east and north) components matter.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] By setting *v*n = 0, it can be seen immediately that (for positive *φ* and *ω*) a movement due east results in an acceleration due south; similarly, setting *v*e = 0, it is seen that a movement due north results in an acceleration due east.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In general, observed horizontally, looking along the direction of the movement causing the acceleration, the acceleration always is turned 90° to the right (for positive *φ*) and of the same size regardless of the horizontal orientation.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Accordingly, an eastward motion (that is, in the same direction as the rotation of the sphere) provides an upward acceleration known as the Eötvös effect, and an upward motion produces an acceleration due west.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Perhaps the most important impact of the Coriolis effect is in the large-scale dynamics of the oceans and the atmosphere.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In meteorology and oceanography, it is convenient to postulate a rotating frame of reference wherein the Earth is stationary.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In accommodation of that provisional postulation, the centrifugal and Coriolis forces are introduced.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Their relative importance is determined by the applicable Rossby numbers.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Tornadoes have high Rossby numbers, so, while tornado-associated centrifugal forces are quite substantial, Coriolis forces associated with tornadoes are for practical purposes negligible.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Because surface ocean currents are driven by the movement of wind over the water's surface, the Coriolis force also affects the movement of ocean currents and cyclones as well.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Many of the ocean's largest currents circulate around warm, high-pressure areas called gyres.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Though the circulation is not as significant as that in the air, the deflection caused by the Coriolis effect is what creates the spiralling pattern in these gyres.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The spiralling wind pattern helps the hurricane form.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The stronger the force from the Coriolis effect, the faster the wind spins and picks up additional energy, increasing the strength of the hurricane.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Air within high-pressure systems rotates in a direction such that the Coriolis force is directed radially inwards, and nearly balanced by the outwardly radial pressure gradient.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] As a result, air travels clockwise around high pressure in the Northern Hemisphere and anticlockwise in the Southern Hemisphere.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Air around low-pressure rotates in the opposite direction, so that the Coriolis force is directed radially outward and nearly balances an inwardly radial pressure gradient.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] If a low-pressure area forms in the atmosphere, air tends to flow in towards it, but is deflected perpendicular to its velocity by the Coriolis force.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] A system of equilibrium can then establish itself creating circular movement, or a cyclonic flow.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Because the Rossby number is low, the force balance is largely between the pressure-gradient force acting towards the low-pressure area and the Coriolis force acting away from the center of the low pressure.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Instead of flowing down the gradient, large scale motions in the atmosphere and ocean tend to occur perpendicular to the pressure gradient.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] On a non-rotating planet, fluid would flow along the straightest possible line, quickly eliminating pressure gradients.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The geostrophic balance is thus very different from the case of "inertial motions" (see below), which explains why mid-latitude cyclones are larger by an order of magnitude than inertial circle flow would be.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] This pattern of deflection, and the direction of movement, is called Buys-Ballot's law.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In the atmosphere, the pattern of flow is called a cyclone.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In the Northern Hemisphere the direction of movement around a low-pressure area is anticlockwise.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In the Southern Hemisphere, the direction of movement is clockwise because the rotational dynamics is a mirror image there.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] At high altitudes, outward-spreading air rotates in the opposite direction.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Cyclones rarely form along the equator due to the weak Coriolis effect present in this region.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] An air or water mass moving with speed $v\,$ subject only to the Coriolis force travels in a circular trajectory called an *inertial circle*.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Since the force is directed at right angles to the motion of the particle, it moves with a constant speed around a circle whose radius R is given by: $R={\frac {v}{f}}$ where f is the Coriolis parameter $2\Omega \sin \varphi$ , introduced above (where $\varphi$ is the latitude).
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The time taken for the mass to complete a full circle is therefore $2\pi /f$ .
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The Coriolis parameter typically has a mid-latitude value of about 10−4 s−1; hence for a typical atmospheric speed of 10 m/s (22 mph), the radius is 100 km (62 mi) with a period of about 17 hours.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] For an ocean current with a typical speed of 10 cm/s (0.22 mph), the radius of an inertial circle is 1 km (0.6 mi).
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] These inertial circles are clockwise in the Northern Hemisphere (where trajectories are bent to the right) and anticlockwise in the Southern Hemisphere.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] If the rotating system is a parabolic turntable, then f is constant and the trajectories are exact circles.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] On a rotating planet, f varies with latitude and the paths of particles do not form exact circles.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Since the parameter f varies as the sine of the latitude, the radius of the oscillations associated with a given speed are smallest at the poles (latitude of ±90°), and increase toward the equator.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The Coriolis effect strongly affects the large-scale oceanic and atmospheric circulation, leading to the formation of robust features like jet streams and western boundary currents.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Such features are in geostrophic balance, meaning that the Coriolis and *pressure gradient* forces balance each other.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Coriolis acceleration is also responsible for the propagation of many types of waves in the ocean and atmosphere, including Rossby waves and Kelvin waves.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] It is also instrumental in the so-called Ekman dynamics in the ocean, and in the establishment of the large-scale ocean flow pattern called the Sverdrup balance.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The practical impact of the "Coriolis effect" is mostly caused by the horizontal acceleration component produced by horizontal motion.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] There are other components of the Coriolis effect.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Westward-traveling objects are deflected downwards, while eastward-traveling objects are deflected upwards.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] This aspect of the Coriolis effect is greatest near the equator.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The force produced by the Eötvös effect is similar to the horizontal component, but the much larger vertical forces due to gravity and pressure suggest that it is unimportant in the hydrostatic equilibrium.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] However, in the atmosphere, winds are associated with small deviations of pressure from the hydrostatic equilibrium.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In the tropical atmosphere, the order of magnitude of the pressure deviations is so small that the contribution of the Eötvös effect to the pressure deviations is considerable.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In addition, objects traveling upwards (i.e.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] *in*) are deflected to the west or east respectively.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] This effect is also the greatest near the equator.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Since vertical movement is usually of limited extent and duration, the size of the effect is smaller and requires precise instruments to detect.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] For example, idealized numerical modeling studies suggest that this effect can directly affect tropical large-scale wind field by roughly 10% given long-duration (2 weeks or more) heating or cooling in the atmosphere.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Moreover, in the case of large changes of momentum, such as a spacecraft being launched into orbit, the effect becomes significant.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The fastest and most fuel-efficient path to orbit is a launch from the equator that curves to a directly eastward heading.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Imagine a train that travels through a frictionless railway line along the equator.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Assume that, when in motion, it moves at the necessary speed to complete a trip around the world in one day (465 m/s).
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The Coriolis effect can be considered in three cases: when the train travels west, when it is at rest, and when it travels east.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In each case, the Coriolis effect can be calculated from the rotating frame of reference on Earth first, and then checked against a fixed inertial frame.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] 0.34% of the force of gravity provides the centripetal force needed to achieve the circular motion on that frame of reference.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The remaining force, as measured by a scale, makes the train and passengers "lighter" than in the previous case.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In this case, because it moves in the direction of Earth's rotating frame, the Coriolis term is directed outward from the axis of rotation (up).
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] This upward force makes the train seem lighter still than when at rest.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] From the fixed inertial frame of reference above Earth, the train traveling east now rotates at twice the rate as when it was at rest—so the amount of centripetal force needed to cause that circular path increases leaving less force from gravity to act on the track.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] This is what the Coriolis term accounts for on the previous paragraph.As a final check one can imagine a frame of reference rotating along with the train.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Such frame would be rotating at twice the angular velocity as Earth's rotating frame.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The resulting centrifugal force component for that imaginary frame would be greater.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Since the train and its passengers are at rest, that would be the only component in that frame explaining again why the train and the passengers are lighter than in the previous two cases.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] This also explains why high-speed projectiles that travel west are deflected down, and those that travel east are deflected up.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] This vertical component of the Coriolis effect is called the Eötvös effect.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The above example can be used to explain why the Eötvös effect starts diminishing when an object is traveling westward as its tangential speed increases above Earth's rotation (465 m/s).
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] If the westward train in the above example increases speed, part of the force of gravity that pushes against the track accounts for the centripetal force needed to keep it in circular motion on the inertial frame.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Once the train doubles its westward speed at 930 m/s (2,100 mph) that centripetal force becomes equal to the force the train experiences when it stops.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] From the inertial frame, in both cases it rotates at the same speed but in the opposite directions.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Thus, the force is the same cancelling completely the Eötvös effect.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Any object that moves westward at a speed above 930 m/s (2,100 mph) experiences an upward force instead.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In the figure, the Eötvös effect is illustrated for a 10-kilogram (22 lb) object on the train at different speeds.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The parabolic shape is because the centripetal force is proportional to the square of the tangential speed.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] On the inertial frame, the bottom of the parabola is centered at the origin.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The offset is because this argument uses the Earth's rotating frame of reference.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The graph shows that the Eötvös effect is not symmetrical, and that the resulting downward force experienced by an object that travels west at high velocity is less than the resulting upward force when it travels east at the same speed.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Contrary to popular misconception, bathtubs, toilets, and other water receptacles do not drain in opposite directions in the Northern and Southern Hemispheres.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] This is because the magnitude of the Coriolis force is negligible at this scale.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Forces determined by the initial conditions of the water (e.g. the geometry of the drain, the geometry of the receptacle, preexisting momentum of the water, etc.) are likely to be orders of magnitude greater than the Coriolis force and hence will determine the direction of water rotation, if any.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] For example, identical toilets flushed in both hemispheres drain in the same direction, and this direction is determined mostly by the shape of the toilet bowl.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Under real-world conditions, the Coriolis force does not influence the direction of water flow perceptibly.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Without such careful preparation, the Coriolis effect will be much smaller than various other influences on drain direction such as any residual rotation of the water and the geometry of the container.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In 1962, Ascher Shapiro performed an experiment at MIT to test the Coriolis force on a large basin of water, 2 meters (6 ft 7 in) across, with a small wooden cross above the plug hole to display the direction of rotation, covering it and waiting for at least 24 hours for the water to settle.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Under these precise laboratory conditions, he demonstrated the effect and consistent counterclockwise rotation.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The experiment required extreme precision, since the acceleration due to Coriolis effect is only $3\times 10^{-7}$ that of gravity.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The vortex was measured by a cross made of two slivers of wood pinned above the draining hole.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] It takes 20 minutes to drain, and the cross starts turning only around 15 minutes.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] At the end it is turning at 1 rotation every 3 to 4 seconds.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Trefethen reported clockwise rotation in the Southern Hemisphere at the University of Sydney in five tests with settling times of 18 h or more.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The Coriolis force is important in external ballistics for calculating the trajectories of very long-range artillery shells.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The most famous historical example was the Paris gun, used by the Germans during World War I to bombard Paris from a range of about 120 km (75 mi).
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The Coriolis force minutely changes the trajectory of a bullet, affecting accuracy at extremely long distances.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] It is adjusted for by accurate long-distance shooters, such as snipers.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] At the latitude of Sacramento, California, a 1,000 yd (910 m) northward shot would be deflected 2.8 in (71 mm) to the right.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] There is also a vertical component, explained in the Eötvös effect section above, which causes westward shots to hit low, and eastward shots to hit high.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The effects of the Coriolis force on ballistic trajectories should not be confused with the curvature of the paths of missiles, satellites, and similar objects when the paths are plotted on two-dimensional (flat) maps, such as the Mercator projection.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The projections of the three-dimensional curved surface of the Earth to a two-dimensional surface (the map) necessarily results in distorted features.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The apparent curvature of the path is a consequence of the sphericity of the Earth and would occur even in a non-rotating frame.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The Coriolis force on a moving projectile depends on velocity components in all three directions, latitude, and azimuth.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The directions are typically downrange (the direction that the gun is initially pointing), vertical, and cross-range.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] To demonstrate the Coriolis effect, a parabolic turntable can be used.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] On a flat turntable, the inertia of a co-rotating object forces it off the edge.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] (See banked turn.) This carefully contoured surface allows the Coriolis force to be displayed in isolation.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Discs cut from cylinders of dry ice can be used as pucks, moving around almost frictionlessly over the surface of the parabolic turntable, allowing effects of Coriolis on dynamic phenomena to show themselves.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] To get a view of the motions as seen from the reference frame rotating with the turntable, a video camera is attached to the turntable so as to co-rotate with the turntable, with results as shown in the figure.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In the left panel of the figure, which is the viewpoint of a stationary observer, the gravitational force in the inertial frame pulling the object toward the center (bottom ) of the dish is proportional to the distance of the object from the center.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] A centripetal force of this form causes the elliptical motion.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In the right panel, which shows the viewpoint of the rotating frame, the inward gravitational force in the rotating frame (the same force as in the inertial frame) is balanced by the outward centrifugal force (present only in the rotating frame).
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] With these two forces balanced, in the rotating frame the only unbalanced force is Coriolis (also present only in the rotating frame), and the motion is an *inertial circle*.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Analysis and observation of circular motion in the rotating frame is a simplification compared with analysis and observation of elliptical motion in the inertial frame.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Because this reference frame rotates several times a minute rather than only once a day like the Earth, the Coriolis acceleration produced is many times larger and so easier to observe on small time and spatial scales than is the Coriolis acceleration caused by the rotation of the Earth.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In a manner of speaking, the Earth is analogous to such a turntable.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The rotation has caused the planet to settle on a spheroid shape, such that the normal force, the gravitational force and the centrifugal force exactly balance each other on a "horizontal" surface.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The Coriolis effect caused by the rotation of the Earth can be seen indirectly through the motion of a Foucault pendulum.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] A practical application of the Coriolis effect is the mass flow meter, an instrument that measures the mass flow rate and density of a fluid flowing through a tube.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The operating principle involves inducing a vibration of the tube through which the fluid passes.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The vibration, though not completely circular, provides the rotating reference frame that gives rise to the Coriolis effect.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] While specific methods vary according to the design of the flow meter, sensors monitor and analyze changes in frequency, phase shift, and amplitude of the vibrating flow tubes.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The changes observed represent the mass flow rate and density of the fluid.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In polyatomic molecules, the molecule motion can be described by a rigid body rotation and internal vibration of atoms about their equilibrium position.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] As a result of the vibrations of the atoms, the atoms are in motion relative to the rotating coordinate system of the molecule.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Coriolis effects are therefore present, and make the atoms move in a direction perpendicular to the original oscillations.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] This leads to a mixing in molecular spectra between the rotational and vibrational levels, from which Coriolis coupling constants can be determined.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Flies (Diptera) and some moths (Lepidoptera) exploit the Coriolis effect in flight with specialized appendages and organs that relay information about the angular velocity of their bodies.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] Coriolis forces resulting from linear motion of these appendages are detected within the rotating frame of reference of the insects' bodies.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In the case of flies, their specialized appendages are dumbbell shaped organs located just behind their wings called "halteres".
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The fly's halteres oscillate in a plane at the same beat frequency as the main wings so that any body rotation results in lateral deviation of the halteres from their plane of motion.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In moths, their antennae are known to be responsible for the *sensing* of Coriolis forces in the similar manner as with the halteres in flies.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In both flies and moths, a collection of mechanosensors at the base of the appendage are sensitive to deviations at the beat frequency, correlating to rotation in the pitch and roll planes, and at twice the beat frequency, correlating to rotation in the yaw plane.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] In astronomy, Lagrangian points are five positions in the orbital plane of two large orbiting bodies where a small object affected only by gravity can maintain a stable position relative to the two large bodies.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The first three Lagrangian points (L1, L2, L3) lie along the line connecting the two large bodies, while the last two points (L4 and L5) each form an equilateral triangle with the two large bodies.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The L4 and L5 points, although they correspond to maxima of the effective potential in the coordinate frame that rotates with the two large bodies, are stable due to the Coriolis effect.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] The stability can result in orbits around just L4 or L5, known as tadpole orbits, where trojans can be found.
[src:gyroscope-mems/coriolis-force] It can also result in orbits that encircle L3, L4, and L5, known as horseshoe orbits.
[src:gyroscope-mems/fibre-optic-gyroscope] A **fibre-optic gyroscope** (**FOG**) senses changes in orientation using the Sagnac effect, thus performing the function of a mechanical gyroscope.
[src:gyroscope-mems/fibre-optic-gyroscope] However its principle of operation is instead based on the interference of light which has passed through a coil of optical fibre, which can be as long as 5 kilometres (3 mi).
[src:gyroscope-mems/fibre-optic-gyroscope] Two beams from a laser are injected into the same fibre but in opposite directions.
[src:gyroscope-mems/fibre-optic-gyroscope] Due to the Sagnac effect, the beam travelling against the rotation experiences a slightly shorter path delay than the other beam.
[src:gyroscope-mems/fibre-optic-gyroscope] The resulting differential phase shift is measured through interferometry, thus translating one component of the angular velocity into a shift of the interference pattern which is measured photometrically.
[src:gyroscope-mems/fibre-optic-gyroscope] Beam splitting optics split light from a laser diode (or other laser light source) into two waves propagating in both clockwise and anticlockwise directions through a coil consisting of many turns of optical fibre.
[src:gyroscope-mems/fibre-optic-gyroscope] The strength of the Sagnac effect is dependent on the *effective area* of the closed optical path: this is not simply the geometric area of the loop but is also increased by the number of turns in the coil.
[src:gyroscope-mems/fibre-optic-gyroscope] The FOG was first proposed by Vali and Shorthill in 1976.
[src:gyroscope-mems/fibre-optic-gyroscope] Development of both the passive interferometer type of FOG, or IFOG, and a newer concept, the passive ring resonator FOG, or RFOG, is proceeding in many companies and establishments worldwide.
[src:gyroscope-mems/fibre-optic-gyroscope] A FOG provides extremely precise rotational rate information, in part because of its lack of cross-axis sensitivity to vibration, acceleration, and shock.
[src:gyroscope-mems/fibre-optic-gyroscope] Unlike the classic spinning-mass gyroscope or resonant/mechanical gyroscopes, the FOG has no moving parts and doesn't rely on inertial resistance to movement.
[src:gyroscope-mems/fibre-optic-gyroscope] Hence, the FOG is an excellent alternative to a mechanical gyroscope.
[src:gyroscope-mems/fibre-optic-gyroscope] Because of their intrinsic reliability and long lifetime, FOGs are used for high performance space applications and military inertial navigation systems.
[src:gyroscope-mems/fibre-optic-gyroscope] Fibre-optic gyroscopes are increasingly valued for their resilience against Global Navigation Satellite System (GNSS) jamming and spoofing.
[src:gyroscope-mems/fibre-optic-gyroscope] Because FOGs operate as autonomous inertial sensors and do not rely on external satellite signals to determine rotational movement or heading, they can continue providing accurate navigation and attitude data during GPS interference events.
[src:gyroscope-mems/fibre-optic-gyroscope] This has become particularly important in maritime and defence applications, where deliberate GNSS disruption has increased significantly in regions such as the Black Sea, Baltic Sea, Eastern Mediterranean, and Strait of Hormuz.
[src:gyroscope-mems/fibre-optic-gyroscope] The FOG typically shows a higher resolution than a ring laser gyroscope.
[src:gyroscope-mems/fibre-optic-gyroscope] FOGs are implemented in both open-loop and closed-loop configurations.
[src:gyroscope-mems/fibre-optic-gyroscope] Like all other gyroscope technologies and depending on detailed FOG design, FOGs may require initial calibration (determining which indication corresponds to zero angular velocity).
[src:gyroscope-mems/fibre-optic-gyroscope] Some FOG designs are somewhat sensitive to vibrations.
[src:gyroscope-mems/fibre-optic-gyroscope] However, when coupled with multiple-axis FOG and accelerometers and hybridized with Global Navigational Satellite System (GNSS) data, the impact is mitigated, making FOG systems suitable for high shock environments, including gun pointing systems for 105mm and 155mm howitzers.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] A **gyroscope** (from Ancient Greek γῦρος *gŷros* 'round' and σκοπέω *skopéō* 'to look') is a device used for measuring or maintaining orientation and angular velocity.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] It is a spinning wheel or disc in which the axis of rotation (spin axis) is free to assume any orientation by itself.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] When rotating, the orientation of this axis is unaffected by tilting or rotation of the mounting, due to the conservation of angular momentum.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Gyroscopes based on other operating principles also exist, such as the microchip-packaged MEMS gyroscopes found in electronic devices (sometimes called **gyrometers**), solid-state ring lasers, fibre optic gyroscopes, and the extremely sensitive quantum gyroscope.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Applications of gyroscopes include inertial navigation systems, such as in the Hubble Space Telescope, or inside the steel hull of a submerged submarine.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Due to their precision, gyroscopes are also used in gyrotheodolites to maintain direction in tunnel mining.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Gyroscopes can be used to construct gyrocompasses, which complement or replace magnetic compasses (in ships, aircraft and spacecraft, vehicles in general), to assist in stability (bicycles, motorcycles, and ships; known as **gyrostabilization**) or be used as part of an inertial guidance system.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] MEMS (microelectromechanical system) gyroscopes are popular in some consumer electronics, such as smartphones.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] A gyroscope is an instrument, consisting of a wheel mounted into two or three gimbals providing pivoted supports, for allowing the wheel to rotate about a single axis.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] A set of three gimbals, one mounted on the other with orthogonal pivot axes, may be used to allow a wheel mounted on the innermost gimbal to have an orientation remaining independent of the orientation, in space, of its support.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] In the case of a gyroscope with two gimbals, the outer gimbal, which is the gyroscope frame, is mounted so as to pivot about an axis in its own plane determined by the support.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] This outer gimbal possesses one degree of rotational freedom and its axis possesses none.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The second (inner) gimbal is mounted in the gyroscope frame (outer gimbal) so as to pivot about an axis in its own plane that is always perpendicular to the pivotal axis of the gyroscope frame (outer gimbal).
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] This inner gimbal has two degrees of rotational freedom.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The axle of the spinning wheel (the rotor) defines the spin axis.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The rotor is constrained to spin about an axis, which is always perpendicular to the axis of the inner gimbal.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] So the rotor possesses three degrees of rotational freedom and its axis possesses two.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The rotor responds to a force applied to the input axis by a reaction force to the output axis.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] A gyroscope flywheel will roll or resist about the output axis depending upon whether the output gimbals are of a free or fixed configuration.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] An example of some free-output-gimbal devices is the attitude control gyroscopes used to sense or measure the pitch, roll and yaw attitude angles in a spacecraft or aircraft.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The centre of gravity of the rotor can be in a fixed position.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The rotor simultaneously spins about one axis and is capable of oscillating about the two other axes, and it is free to turn in any direction about the fixed point (except for its inherent resistance caused by rotor spin).
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Some gyroscopes have mechanical equivalents substituted for one or more of the elements.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] For example, the spinning rotor may be suspended in a fluid, instead of being mounted in gimbals.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] A control moment gyroscope (CMG) is an example of a fixed-output-gimbal device that is used on spacecraft to hold or maintain a desired attitude angle or pointing direction using the gyroscopic resistance force.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] In some special cases, the outer gimbal (or its equivalent) may be omitted so that the rotor has only two degrees of freedom.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] In other cases, the centre of gravity of the rotor may be offset from the axis of oscillation, and thus the centre of gravity of the rotor and the centre of suspension of the rotor may not coincide.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Essentially, a gyroscope is a top combined with a pair of gimbals.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Tops were invented in many different civilizations, including classical Greece, Rome, and China.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Most of these were not utilized as instruments.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The first known apparatus similar to a gyroscope (the "Whirling Speculum" or "Serson's Speculum") was invented by John Serson in 1743.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] It was used as a level, to locate the horizon in foggy or misty conditions.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The first instrument used more like an actual gyroscope was made by Johann Bohnenberger of Germany, who first wrote about it in 1817.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Bohnenberger's machine was based on a rotating massive sphere.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Johnson developed a similar device that was based on a rotating disc.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The French mathematician Pierre-Simon Laplace, working at the École Polytechnique in Paris, recommended the machine for use as a teaching aid, and thus it came to the attention of Léon Foucault.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] In 1852, Foucault used it in an experiment demonstrating the rotation of the Earth.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] It was Foucault who gave the device its modern name, in an experiment to see (Greek *skopeein* 'to see') the Earth's rotation (Greek *gyros* 'circle, rotation'), which was visible in the 8 to 10 minutes before friction slowed the spinning rotor.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] In the 1860s, the advent of electric motors made it possible for a gyroscope to spin indefinitely; this led to the first prototype heading indicators, and a rather more complicated device, the gyrocompass.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The first functional gyrocompass was patented in 1904 by German inventor Hermann Anschütz-Kaempfe.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] American Elmer Sperry followed with his own design later that year, and other nations soon realized the military importance of the invention—in an age in which naval prowess was the most significant measure of military power—and created their own gyroscope industries.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The Sperry Gyroscope Company quickly expanded to provide aircraft and naval stabilizers as well, and other gyroscope developers followed suit.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Hurst Mfg Co of Indianapolis started producing the "Hurst gyroscope" a toy gyroscope with a pull string and pedestal.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Manufacture was at some point switched to Chandler Mfg Co (still branded Hurst).
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The product was later renamed to a "Chandler gyroscope", presumably because Chandler Mfg Co. took over rights to the gyroscope.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Chandler continued to produce the toy until the company was purchased by TEDCO Inc. in 1982.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The gyroscope is still produced by TEDCO today.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Similar principles were later employed in the development of inertial navigation systems for ballistic missiles.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] During World War II, the gyroscope became the prime component for aircraft and anti-aircraft gun sights.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] After the war, the race to miniaturize gyroscopes for guided missiles and weapons navigation systems resulted in the development and manufacturing of so-called **midget gyroscopes** that weighed less than 3 ounces (85 g) and had a diameter of approximately 1 inch (2.5 cm).
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Some of these miniaturized gyroscopes could reach a speed of 24,000 revolutions per minute in less than 10 seconds.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Gyroscopes continue to be an engineering challenge.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] For example, the axle bearings have to be extremely accurate.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] A small amount of friction is deliberately introduced to the bearings, since otherwise an accuracy of better than $10^{-7}$ of an inch (2.5 nm) would be required.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Three-axis MEMS-based gyroscopes are also used in portable electronic devices such as tablets, smartphones, and smartwatches.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] This adds to the 3-axis acceleration sensing ability available on previous generations of devices.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Together these sensors provide 6 component motion sensing; accelerometers for X, Y, and Z movement, and gyroscopes for measuring the extent and rate of rotation in space (roll, pitch and yaw).
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Some devices additionally incorporate a magnetometer to provide absolute angular measurements relative to the Earth's magnetic field.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Newer MEMS-based inertial measurement units incorporate up to all nine axes of sensing in a single integrated circuit package, providing inexpensive and widely available motion sensing.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] All spinning objects have gyroscopic properties.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The main properties that an object can experience in any gyroscopic motion are rigidity in space and precession.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Rigidity in space describes the principle that a gyroscope remains in the fixed position on the plane in which it is spinning, unaffected by the Earth's rotation. such as with a rotating bike wheel.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Early forms of gyroscope (not then known by the name) were used to demonstrate the principle.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] where $\phi '$ represents precession, $\psi '$ is represented by spin, $\theta$ is the nutation angle, and I represents inertia along its respective axis.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] This relation is only valid when the moments along the Y and Z axes are equal to 0.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The equation can be further reduced noting that the angular velocity along the z-axis is equal to the sum of the precession and the spin: $\omega _{z}=\phi '\cos \theta +\psi '$ , Where $\omega _{z}$ represents the angular velocity along the z axis.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Gyroscopic precession is torque induced.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] It is the rate of change of the angular momentum that is produced by the applied torque.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Precession produces counterintuitive dynamic results such as a spinning top not falling over.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Precession is used in aerospace applications for sensing changes of attitude and direction.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] A Steadicam rig was employed during the filming of the 1983 film *Return of the Jedi*, in conjunction with two gyroscopes for extra stabilization, to film the background plates for the speeder bike chase.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Steadicam inventor Garrett Brown operated the shot, walking through a redwood forest, running the camera at one frame per second.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] When projected at 24 frames per second, it gave the impression of flying through the air at perilous speeds.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The heading indicator or directional gyro has an axis of rotation that is set horizontally, pointing north.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Unlike a magnetic compass, it does not seek north.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] When being used in an airplane, for example, it will slowly drift away from north and will need to be reoriented periodically, using a magnetic compass as a reference.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Unlike a directional gyro or heading indicator, a gyrocompass seeks north.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] It detects the rotation of the Earth about its axis and seeks the *true* north, rather than the *magnetic* north.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Gyrocompasses usually have built-in damping to prevent overshoot when re-calibrating from sudden movement.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] By determining an object's acceleration and integrating over time, the velocity of the object can be calculated.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Integrating again, position can be determined.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The simplest accelerometer is a weight that is free to move horizontally, which is attached to a spring and a device to measure the tension in the spring.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] This can be improved by introducing a counteracting force to push the weight back and to measure the force needed to prevent the weight from moving.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] A more complicated design consists of a gyroscope with a weight on one of the axes.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The device will react to the force generated by the weight when it is accelerated, by integrating that force to produce a velocity.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] A **gyrostat** consists of a massive flywheel concealed in a solid casing.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Its behaviour on a table, or with various modes of suspension or support, serves to illustrate the curious reversal of the ordinary laws of static equilibrium due to the gyrostatic behaviour of the interior invisible flywheel when rotated rapidly.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The first gyrostat was designed by Lord Kelvin to illustrate the more complicated state of motion of a spinning body when free to wander about on a horizontal plane, like a top spun on the pavement, or a bicycle on the road.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Kelvin also made use of gyrostats to develop mechanical theories of the elasticity of matter and of the ether.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] In modern continuum mechanics there is a variety of these models, based on ideas of Lord Kelvin.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] They represent a specific type of Cosserat theories (suggested for the first time by Eugène Cosserat and François Cosserat), which can be used for description of artificially made smart materials as well as of other complex media.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] One of them, so-called Kelvin's medium, has the same equations as magnetic insulators near the state of magnetic saturation in the approximation of quasimagnetostatics.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] In modern times, the gyrostat concept is used in the design of attitude control systems for orbiting spacecraft and satellites.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] For instance, the Mir space station had three pairs of internally mounted flywheels known as *gyrodynes* or control moment gyroscopes.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] In physics, there are several systems whose dynamical equations resemble the equations of motion of a gyrostat.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] A microelectromechanical systems (MEMS) gyroscope is a miniaturized gyroscope found in electronic devices.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] It takes the idea of the Foucault pendulum and uses a vibrating element.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] This kind of gyroscope was first used in military applications but has since been adopted for increasing commercial use.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The hemispherical resonator gyroscope (HRG), also called a wine-glass gyroscope or mushroom gyro, makes use of a thin solid-state hemispherical shell, anchored by a thick stem.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] This shell is driven to a flexural resonance by electrostatic forces generated by electrodes which are deposited directly onto separate fused-quartz structures that surround the shell.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Gyroscopic effect is obtained from the inertial property of the flexural standing waves.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] A vibrating structure gyroscope (VSG), also called a Coriolis vibratory gyroscope (CVG), uses a resonator made of different metallic alloys.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] It takes a position between the low-accuracy, low-cost MEMS gyroscope and the higher-accuracy and higher-cost fiber optic gyroscope.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Accuracy parameters are increased by using low-intrinsic damping materials, resonator vacuumization, and digital electronics to reduce temperature dependent drift and instability of control signals.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] High quality wine-glass resonators are used for precise sensors like HRG.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] A dynamically tuned gyroscope (DTG) is a rotor suspended by a universal joint with flexure pivots.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The flexure spring stiffness is independent of spin rate.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] However, the dynamic inertia (from the gyroscopic reaction effect) from the gimbal provides negative spring stiffness proportional to the square of the spin speed (Howe and Savet, 1964; Lawrence, 1998).
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Therefore, at a particular speed, called the tuning speed, the two moments cancel each other, freeing the rotor from torque, a necessary condition for an ideal gyroscope.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] A ring laser gyroscope relies on the Sagnac effect to measure rotation by measuring the shifting interference pattern of a beam split into two separate beams which travel around the ring in opposite directions.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] When the Boeing 757-200 entered service in 1983, it was equipped with the first suitable ring laser gyroscope.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] This gyroscope took many years to develop, and the experimental models went through many changes before it was deemed ready for production by the engineers and managers of Honeywell and Boeing.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] It was an outcome of the competition with mechanical gyroscopes, which kept improving.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The reason Honeywell, of all companies, chose to develop the laser gyro was that they were the only one that did not have a successful line of mechanical gyroscopes, so they would not be competing against themselves.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The first problem they had to solve was that with laser gyros rotations below a certain minimum could not be detected at all, due to a problem called "lock-in", whereby the two beams act like coupled oscillators and pull each other's frequencies toward convergence and therefore zero output.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The solution was to shake the gyro rapidly so that it never settled into lock-in.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Paradoxically, too regular of a dithering motion produced an accumulation of short periods of lock-in when the device was at rest at the extremities of its shaking motion.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] This was cured by applying a random white noise to the vibration.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The material of the block was also changed from quartz to a new glass ceramic Cer-Vit, made by Owens Corning, because of helium leaks.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] A fiber optic gyroscope also uses the interference of light to detect mechanical rotation.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The two-halves of the split beam travel in opposite directions in a coil of fiber optic cable as long as 5 km.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Like the ring laser gyroscope, it makes use of the Sagnac effect.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] A London moment gyroscope relies on the quantum-mechanical phenomenon, whereby a spinning superconductor generates a magnetic field whose axis lines up exactly with the spin axis of the gyroscopic rotor.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] A magnetometer determines the orientation of the generated field, which is interpolated to determine the axis of rotation.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Gyroscopes of this type can be extremely accurate and stable.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] For example, those used in the Gravity Probe B experiment measured changes in gyroscope spin axis orientation to better than 0.5 milliarcseconds (1.4×10−7 degrees, or about 2.4×10−9 radians) over a one-year period.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] This is equivalent to an angular separation the width of a human hair viewed from 32 kilometers (20 mi) away.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The GP-B gyro consists of a nearly-perfect spherical rotating mass made of fused quartz, which provides a dielectric support for a thin layer of niobium superconducting material.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] To eliminate friction found in conventional bearings, the rotor assembly is centered by the electric field from six electrodes.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] After the initial spin-up by a jet of helium which brings the rotor to 4,000 RPM, the polished gyroscope housing is evacuated to an ultra-high vacuum to further reduce drag on the rotor.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Provided the suspension electronics remain powered, the extreme rotational symmetry, lack of friction, and low drag will allow the angular momentum of the rotor to keep it spinning for about 15,000 years.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] A sensitive DC SQUID that can discriminate changes as small as one quantum, or about 2 ×10−15 Wb, is used to monitor the gyroscope.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] A precession, or tilt, in the orientation of the rotor causes the London moment magnetic field to shift relative to the housing.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The moving field passes through a superconducting pickup loop fixed to the housing, inducing a small electric current.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The current produces a voltage across a shunt resistance, which is resolved to spherical coordinates by a microprocessor.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The system is designed to minimize Lorentz torque on the rotor.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The main rotor of a helicopter acts like a gyroscope.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Its motion is influenced by the principle of gyroscopic precession which is the concept that a force applied to a spinning object will have a maximum reaction approximately 90 degrees later.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The reaction may differ from 90 degrees when other stronger forces are in play.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] To change direction, helicopters must adjust the pitch angle and the angle of attack.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Gyro X prototype vehicle created by Alex Tremulis and Thomas Summers in 1967.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The car utilized gyroscopic precession to drive on two wheels.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] An assembly consisting of a flywheel mounted in a gimbal housing under the hood of the vehicle acted as a large gyroscope.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The flywheel was rotated by hydraulic pumps creating a gyroscopic effect on the vehicle.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] A precessional ram was responsible for rotating the gyroscope to change the direction of the precessional force to counteract any forces causing the vehicle imbalance.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The one-of-a-kind prototype is now at the Lane Motor Museum in Nashville, Tennessee.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] In addition to being used in compasses, aircraft, computer pointing devices, etc., gyroscopes have been introduced into consumer electronics.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Since the gyroscope allows the calculation of orientation and rotation, designers have incorporated them into modern technology.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] The integration of the gyroscope has allowed for more accurate recognition of movement within a 3D space than the previous lone accelerometer within a number of smartphones.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Gyroscopes in consumer electronics are frequently combined with accelerometers for more robust direction- and motion-sensing.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Examples of such applications include smartphones such as the Samsung Galaxy Note 4, HTC Titan, Nexus 5, iPhone 5s, Nokia 808 PureView and Sony Xperia, game console peripherals such as the PlayStation 3 controller and the Wii Remote, and virtual reality headsets such as the Oculus Rift.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Some features of Android phones like PhotoSphere or 360 Camera and to use VR gadget do not work without a gyroscope sensor in the phone.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Nintendo has integrated a gyroscope into the Wii console's Wii Remote controller by an additional piece of hardware called "Wii MotionPlus".
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] It is also included in the 3DS, Wii U GamePad, and Nintendo Switch Joy-Con and Pro controllers, which detect movement when turning and shaking.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] Cruise ships use gyroscopes to level motion-sensitive devices such as self-leveling pool tables.
[src:gyroscope-mems/gyroscope] An electric powered flywheel gyroscope inserted in a bicycle wheel is sold as an alternative to training wheels.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] A **ring laser gyroscope** (**RLG**) consists of a ring laser having two independent counter-propagating resonant modes over the same path; the difference in phase is used to detect rotation.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] It operates on the principle of the Sagnac effect which shifts the nulls of the internal standing wave pattern in response to angular rotation.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] Interference between the counter-propagating beams, observed externally, results in motion of the standing wave pattern, and thus indicates rotation.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] The first experimental ring laser gyroscope was demonstrated in the US by Macek and Davis in 1963.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] Various organizations worldwide subsequently developed ring-laser technology further.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] Many tens of thousands of RLGs are operating in inertial navigation systems and have established high accuracy, with better than 0.01°/hour bias uncertainty, and mean time between failures in excess of 60,000 hours.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] Ring laser gyroscopes can be used as the stable elements (for one degree of freedom each) in an inertial reference system.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] One key advantage of the RLG is that there are no moving parts apart from the dither motor assembly (see further description below).
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] Compared to the conventional spinning gyroscope, this means there is no friction, which eliminates a significant source of drift.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] Additionally, the entire unit is compact, lightweight and highly durable, making it suitable for use in mobile systems such as aircraft, missiles, and satellites.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] Unlike a mechanical gyroscope, the device does not resist changes to its orientation.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] Contemporary applications of the ring laser gyroscope include an embedded GPS capability to further enhance accuracy of RLG inertial navigation systems on military aircraft, commercial airliners, ships, and spacecraft.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] These hybrid INS/GPS units have replaced their mechanical counterparts in most applications.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] The measured noise level is below the calculated shot noise for a RLG where the counterpopagating beams are considered two coherent totally independent modes.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] Actually this discrepancy is supposed to be related to cross-coupling among the two modes.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] According to the Sagnac effect, rotation induces a small difference between the time it takes light to traverse the ring in the two directions.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] This introduces a tiny separation between the frequencies of the counter-propagating beams, a motion of the standing wave pattern within the ring, and thus a beat pattern when those two beams interfere outside the ring.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] Therefore, the net shift of that interference pattern follows the rotation of the unit in the plane of the ring.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] RLGs, while more accurate than mechanical gyroscopes, suffer from an effect known as "lock-in" at very slow rotation rates.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] When the ring laser is hardly rotating, the frequencies of the counter-propagating laser modes become almost identical.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] In this case, crosstalk between the counter-propagating beams can allow for injection locking, so that the standing wave "gets stuck" in a preferred phase, thus locking the frequency of each beam to that of the other, rather than responding to gradual rotation.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] Forced dithering can largely overcome this problem.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] The ring laser cavity is rotated clockwise and anti-clockwise about its axis using a mechanical spring driven at its resonance frequency.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] This ensures that the angular velocity of the system is usually far from the lock-in threshold.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] Typical rates are 400 Hz, with a peak dither velocity on the order of 1 degree per second.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] Dither does not fix the lock-in problem completely, as each time the direction of rotation is reversed, a short time interval exists in which the rotation rate is near zero and lock-in briefly can occur.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] If a pure frequency oscillation is maintained, these small lock-in intervals can accumulate.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] This was remedied by introducing noise to the 400 Hz vibration.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] A different approach to avoiding lock-in is embodied in the Multioscillator Ring Laser Gyroscope, wherein what is effectively two independent ring lasers (each having two counterpropagating beams) of opposite circular polarization coexist in the same ring resonator.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] The resonator incorporates polarization rotation (via a nonplanar geometry) which splits the fourfold-degenerate cavity mode (two directions, two polarizations each) into right- and left-circular-polarized modes separated by many hundreds of MHz, each having two counterpropagating beams.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] One frequency increases and one decreases, when inertial rotation is present; the two frequencies are measured and then digitally subtracted to finally yield the net Sagnac-effect frequency splitting and thus determine the rotation rate.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] The Faraday bias frequency is chosen to be higher than any anticipated rotation-induced frequency difference, so the two counterpropagating waves have no opportunity to lock-in.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] Manufacturers of RLG-based navigation systems (generally called "Inertial Measurement Units" or "Inertial Reference Units" (the terms being interchangeable) include Honeywell, Sperry, Kearfott, Litton, and others.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] Honeywell is probably the most well known with several versions having various levels of performance for applications ranging from missiles to commercial and military aircraft.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] The GG1320 shown above is typical of the latter with each axis in a separate block.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] Kearfott's KI-4921 implements all three axes in a single monolithic block with performance similar to that of the GG1320 but is much more compact and has fewer parts.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] The KI-4921 (shown above) is used for applications in sea navigation like submarines.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] Its monolithic RLG block would fit comfortably inside a baseball.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] There is also a higher performance KI-4902 which is similar in design but roughly 50 percent larger.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] A related device is the fibre optic gyroscope which also operates on the basis of the Sagnac effect, but in which the ring is not a part of the laser.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] Rather, an external laser injects counter-propagating beams into an optical fiber ring, where rotation causes a relative phase shift between those beams when interfered after their pass through the fiber ring.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] The phase shift is proportional to the rate of rotation.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] This is less sensitive in a single traverse of the ring than the RLG, in which the externally observed phase shift is proportional to the accumulated rotation itself, not its derivative.
[src:gyroscope-mems/ring-laser-gyroscope] However, the sensitivity of the fiber optic gyro is enhanced by having a long optical fiber, coiled for compactness, in which the Sagnac effect is multiplied according to the number of turns.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] A **vibrating structure gyroscope** (**VSG**), defined by the IEEE as a **Coriolis vibratory gyroscope** (**CVG**), is a gyroscope that uses a vibrating (as opposed to rotating) structure as its orientation reference.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] A VSG functions much like the halteres of flies (insects in the order Diptera).
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] The underlying physical principle is that a vibrating object tends to continue vibrating in the same plane even if its support rotates.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] The Coriolis effect causes the object to exert a force on its support, and by measuring this force the rate of rotation can be determined.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] Vibrating structure gyroscopes are simpler and cheaper than conventional rotating gyroscopes of similar accuracy.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] Inexpensive VSGs manufactured with micro-electromechanical systems (MEMS) technology are widely used in smartphones, gaming devices, cameras and many other applications.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] Consider two proof masses vibrating in plane (as in a MEMS gyro) at frequency $\omega _{r}$ .
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] The Coriolis effect induces an acceleration on the proof masses equal to $a_{\mathrm {c} }=2(\Omega \times v)$ , where v is the velocity and $\Omega$ is the angular rate of rotation.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] The in-plane velocity of the proof masses is given by $v=x_{\text{ip}}\omega _{r}\cos(\omega _{r}t)$ , if the in-plane position at time t is given by $x_{\text{ip}}=\sin(\omega _{r}t)$ .
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] in the plane of and perpendicular to the driven proof mass motion.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] By measuring $y_{\text{op}}$ , the rate of rotation $\Omega$ can thus be determined.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] This type of gyroscope was developed by GEC-Marconi and Ferranti in the 1980s using metal alloys with attached piezoelectric elements and a single-piece piezoceramic design.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] In the 1990s, CRGs with magneto-electric excitation and readout were produced by American-based Inertial Engineering, Inc. in California, and piezoceramic variants by Watson Industries.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] A recently-patented variant by Innalabs uses a cylindrical resonator design made from Elinvar alloy with piezoceramic elements for excitation and pickoff at its bottom.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] This technology gave a substantially increased product life (MTBF > 500,000 hours); its shock resistance (>300g) should qualify it for *tactical* (mid-accuracy) applications.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] The resonator is operated in its second-order resonant mode.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] The Q factor is usually about 20,000; that predetermines its noise and angular random walks.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] Standing waves are elliptically-shaped oscillations with four antinodes and four nodes located circumferentially along the rim.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] The angle between two adjacent antinode–node pairs is 45 degrees.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] One of the elliptical resonant modes is excited to a prescribed amplitude.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] When the device rotates about its sensitive axis (along its inner stem), the resulting Coriolis forces acting on the resonator's vibrating mass elements excite the second resonant mode.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] The angle between major axes of the two modes is also 45 degrees.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] A closed loop drives the second resonant mode to zero, and the force required to null this mode is proportional to the input rotation rate.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] This control loop is designated the *force-rebalanced mode*.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] Piezoelectric elements on the resonator produce forces and sense induced motions.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] This electromechanical system provides the low output noise and large dynamic range that demanding applications require, but suffers from intense acoustic noises and high overloads.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] A piezoelectric material can be induced to vibrate, and lateral motion due to Coriolis force can be measured to produce a signal related to the rate of rotation.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] This type of gyroscope uses a pair of test masses driven to resonance.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] Their displacement from the plane of oscillation is measured to produce a signal related to the system's rate of rotation.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] Frederick William Meredith registered a patent for such a device in 1942 while working at the Royal Aircraft Establishment (RAE).
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] Further development was carried out at the RAE in 1958 by G.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] Hobbs, who demonstrated drift of less than one degree per hour, or (2.78×10−4)°/s.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] Modern variants of tactical gyroscopes use doubled tuning forks such as those produced by American manufacturer Systron Donner in California and French manufacturer Safran.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] Also called a hemispherical resonator gyroscope or HRG, a wine-glass resonator uses a thin solid-state hemisphere anchored by a thick stem.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] The hemisphere with its stem is driven to flexural resonance and the nodal points are measured to detect rotation.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] There are two basic variants of such a system: one based on a rate regime of operation (*force-to-rebalance mode*) and another variant based on an integrating regime of operation (*whole-angle mode*).
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] Usually, the latter one is used in combination with a controlled parametric excitation.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] It is possible to use both regimes with the same hardware, which is a feature unique to these gyroscopes.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] For a single-piece design (i.e., the hemispherical cup and stem(s) form a monolithic part) made from high-purity quartz glass, it is possible to reach a Q factor greater than 30–50 million in vacuum, so the corresponding random walks are extremely low.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] The Q is limited by the coating, an extremely thin film of gold or platinum, and by fixture losses.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] Such resonators have to be fine-tuned by ion-beam micro-erosion of the glass or by laser ablation.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] Engineers and researchers in several countries have been working on further improvements of these sophisticated state-of-art technologies.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] Safran and Northrop Grumman are major manufacturers of HRGs.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] A wheel is driven to rotate a fraction of a full turn about its axis.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] The tilt of the wheel is measured to produce a signal related to the rate of rotation.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] Inexpensive vibrating structure microelectromechanical systems (MEMS) gyroscopes have become widely available.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] These are packaged similarly to other integrated circuits and may provide either analogue or digital outputs.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] In many cases, a single part includes gyroscopic sensors for multiple axes.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] Some parts incorporate multiple gyroscopes and accelerometers (or multiple-axis gyroscopes and accelerometers), to achieve output that has six full degrees of freedom.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] These units are called inertial measurement units, or IMUs.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] Panasonic, Bosch, InvenSense, Seiko Epson, Sensonor, Hanking Electronics, STMicroelectronics, Freescale Semiconductor, and Analog Devices are major manufacturers.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] Internally, MEMS gyroscopes use micro-lithographically constructed versions of one or more of the mechanisms outlined above (tuning forks, vibrating wheels, or various designs, similar to TFGs, CRGs, or HRGs).
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] MEMS gyroscopes are used in automotive roll-over prevention and airbag systems, image stabilization, and many other potential applications.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] Automotive yaw sensors can be built around vibrating structure gyroscopes.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] These are used to detect error states in yaw compared to a predicted response when connected as an input to electronic stability control systems in conjunction with a steering wheel sensor.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] Advanced systems could conceivably offer rollover detection based on a second VSG, but it is cheaper to add longitudinal and vertical accelerometers to the existing lateral one to this end.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] The Nintendo Game Boy Advance game WarioWare: Twisted! uses a piezoelectric gyroscope to detect rotational movement.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] The Sony Sixaxis PS3 controller uses a single MEMS gyroscope to measure the sixth axis (yaw).
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] The Nintendo Wii MotionPlus accessory uses multi-axis MEMS gyroscopes provided by InvenSense to augment the motion sensing capabilities of the Wii Remote.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] Most modern smartphones and gaming devices also feature MEMS gyroscopes.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] Vibrating structure gyroscopes are commonly used in radio-controlled helicopters to help control the helicopter's tail rotor and in radio-controlled airplanes to help keep the attitude steady during flight.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] They are also used in multirotor flight controllers, since multirotors are inherently aerodynamically unstable and cannot stay airborne without electronic stabilization.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] Epson Robots uses a quartz MEMS gyroscope, called QMEMS, to detect and control vibrations on their robots.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] This helps the robots position the robot end effector with high precision in high speed and fast-deceleration motion.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] Many image stabilization systems on video and still cameras employ vibrating structure gyroscopes.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] Oscillation can also be induced and controlled in vibrating structure gyroscopes for the positioning of spacecraft such as *Cassini–Huygens*.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] These small hemispherical resonator gyroscopes made of quartz glass operate in vacuum.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] There are also prototypes of elastically-decoupled cylindrical resonator gyroscopes (CRGs) made from high-purity single-crystalline sapphire.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] The high-purity leuko-sapphire has a Q factor an order of value greater than quartz glass used for HRG, but this material is hard and has anisotropy.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] They provide accurate three-axis positioning of the spacecraft and are highly reliable over the years, as they have no moving parts.
[src:gyroscope-mems/vibrating-structure-gyroscope] The Segway uses a vibrating structure gyroscope made by Silicon Sensing Systems to stabilize the operator platform.
